AB  - A review of elasmobranchs caught in the shrimp trawl fisheries of Cuba is presented. The bycatch in the shrimp fisheries is composed of a great diversity of species, predominately fish. The poor selectivity of the shrimp trawl is exemplified in a bycatch ratio that exceeds the target capture. Several studies indicate that the elasmobranch bycatch is mainly juvenile individuals. The elasmobranch families most represented in the bycatch are Dasyatidae and Carcharhinidae. As a consequence of this fishery we expect changes to arise among elasmobranchs populations, with reductions in mean trophic level and the size of the catch. Generally, a larger number of rays are captured than sharks. The lack of studies devoted to understanding elasmobranch bycatch in shrimp trawls, demonstrates the need to increase efforts in this type of research which provides knowledge to improve the management of this group of species. sharks; rays; shrimp trawl fishery
